abstract: A documentary captures the desperation and frustration of Type 1 diabetes patients in a clinical trial.
snippet: A documentary captures the desperation and frustration of Type 1 diabetes patients in a clinical trial.
lead_paragraph: In the three decades since she was first diagnosed with Type 1 diabetes, Lisa Hepner has clung to a vague promise she often heard from doctors convinced medical science was on the cusp of making her body whole again. “Stay strong,” they would say. “A cure is just five years away.”

main: The Long, Long Wait for a Diabetes Cure
print_headline: The Long, Long Wait for a Diabetes Cure

abstract: In “Agatha Christie: An Elusive Woman,” Lucy Worsley revisits the weird story of one of the 20th century’s most popular and enduring authors.
snippet: In “Agatha Christie: An Elusive Woman,” Lucy Worsley revisits the weird story of one of the 20th century’s most popular and enduring authors.
lead_paragraph: Agatha Christie’s best books have crisp dialogue and high-velocity plots. The bad ones have a Mad Libs quality: feeble prose studded with blank spots into which you can picture the prolific Christie plugging a random “BODY PART” or “WEAPON.” In a 1971 study of English crime fiction, Colin Watson snickered that Christie “seems to have been well aware that intelligence and readership-potential are quite unrelated.”

main: Agatha Christie’s Latest Biographer Plumbs a Life of Mystery
print_headline: Of Course Her Life Is a Bit of a Mystery

abstract: Seeing false and toxic information as a potentially expensive liability, companies in and outside the tech industry are angling to hire people who can keep it in check.
snippet: Seeing false and toxic information as a potentially expensive liability, companies in and outside the tech industry are angling to hire people who can keep it in check.
lead_paragraph: In the weeks since Elon Musk took over Twitter, dozens of people responsible for keeping dangerous or inaccurate material in check on the service have posted on LinkedIn that they resigned or lost their jobs. Their statements have drawn a flood of condolences — and attempts to recruit them.

main: Sympathy, and Job Offers, for Twitter’s Misinformation Experts
print_headline: As Misinformation Booms, Specialists Are in Demand
